1
00:01:11,954 --> 00:01:16,497
<i>You will travel far, my little Kal-El.</i>

2
00:01:17,085 --> 00:01:19,243
<i>But we will never leave you...</i>

3
00:01:19,670 --> 00:01:22,339
<i>... even in the face of our deaths.</i>

4
00:01:23,591 --> 00:01:26,129
<i>You will make my strength your own.</i>

5
00:01:27,470 --> 00:01:30,755
<i>You will see my life through your eyes...</i>

6
00:01:31,724 --> 00:01:34,476
<i>... as your life will be seen through mine.</i>

7
00:01:35,811 --> 00:01:41,980
<i>The son becomes the father,
and the father the son.</i>

8
00:05:07,567 --> 00:05:10,105
<i>In spite of your past...</i>

9
00:05:12,363 --> 00:05:15,068
...I know you're a good man.

10
00:05:16,576 --> 00:05:18,367
And all good men...

11
00:05:18,912 --> 00:05:21,403
...deserve a second chance.

12
00:05:29,464 --> 00:05:32,549
From the moment
I received your first letter...

13
00:05:32,718 --> 00:05:35,552
...I knew you were not like the rest.

14
00:05:37,097 --> 00:05:41,011
You came from nothing...

15
00:05:41,643 --> 00:05:44,478
...and you worked so hard
to get where you are.

16
00:05:45,439 --> 00:05:48,273
You might have made a few mistakes.

17
00:05:48,650 --> 00:05:51,437
- Gertrude, for God's sake!
- Damn it, Gertrude, let us in now!

18
00:05:51,820 --> 00:05:57,240
You said that if I helped you
get out of prison...

19
00:05:58,368 --> 00:06:00,906
...you'd take care of me.

20
00:06:01,913 --> 00:06:04,071
And you have.

21
00:06:05,459 --> 00:06:09,670
You've shown me pleasures
that I've never known.

22
00:06:11,381 --> 00:06:13,588
That's why you deserve...

23
00:06:13,759 --> 00:06:15,668
...everything.

24
00:06:19,139 --> 00:06:20,634
I love you...

25
00:06:21,182 --> 00:06:23,222
...Lex Luthor.

26
00:06:39,451 --> 00:06:41,942
Gertrude, let us in. He's a crook.

27
00:06:42,121 --> 00:06:44,160
He doesn't love you, Gertrude!

28
00:06:44,331 --> 00:06:45,706
He's a monster! Gertrude!

29
00:07:03,350 --> 00:07:05,557
- You can keep that.
- Oh, God.

30
00:07:05,728 --> 00:07:07,008
The rest is mine.

31
00:07:13,443 --> 00:07:15,152
We're done.

32
00:07:44,683 --> 00:07:46,842
Bye, Martha.

33
00:10:23,677 --> 00:10:25,753
Oh, Clark.

34
00:10:28,682 --> 00:10:31,518
Oh, my boy.

35
00:11:19,567 --> 00:11:22,237
Will you get that thing out of my face!

36
00:11:28,827 --> 00:11:30,903
Lex, your friends give me the creeps.

37
00:11:31,079 --> 00:11:32,953
Prison is a creepy place, Kitty.

38
00:11:33,123 --> 00:11:35,578
One needs to make creepy friends
in order to survive.

39
00:11:35,750 --> 00:11:38,241
Even a man with my vast talents
is worth less inside...

40
00:11:38,419 --> 00:11:42,287
...than a carton of cigarettes and
a sharp piece of metal in your pocket.

41
00:11:45,969 --> 00:11:49,135
Do you know the story of Prometheus?
No, of course you don't.

42
00:11:49,305 --> 00:11:53,350
Prometheus was a god who stole
the power of fire from the other gods...

43
00:11:53,518 --> 00:11:55,261
...and gave control of it to mortals.

44
00:11:55,436 --> 00:11:58,106
In essence, he gave us technology.
He gave us power.

45
00:11:58,273 --> 00:12:01,807
So we're stealing fire? In the Arctic.

46
00:12:01,985 --> 00:12:05,604
Actually, sort of. You see, whoever
controls technology controls the world.

47
00:12:05,781 --> 00:12:08,449
The Roman Empire ruled the world
because they built roads.

48
00:12:08,616 --> 00:12:11,571
The British Empire ruled the world
because they built ships.

49
00:12:11,745 --> 00:12:15,244
America, the atom bomb,
and so on and so forth.

50
00:12:15,415 --> 00:12:17,075
I just want what Prometheus wanted.

51
00:12:17,459 --> 00:12:21,078
Sounds great, Lex, but you're not a god.

52
00:12:24,132 --> 00:12:27,169
Gods are selfish beings
who fly around in little red capes...

53
00:12:27,344 --> 00:12:29,633
...and don't share their power
with mankind.

54
00:12:29,805 --> 00:12:31,429
Hey, boss.

55
00:12:32,057 --> 00:12:33,682
We found something.

56
00:12:38,606 --> 00:12:41,310
No, I don't wanna be a god.

57
00:12:41,483 --> 00:12:44,568
I just wanna bring fire to the people.

58
00:12:45,654 --> 00:12:49,320
And I want my cut.

59
00:13:32,034 --> 00:13:34,359
Was this his house?

60
00:13:35,163 --> 00:13:37,736
You might think so. Most would.

61
00:13:37,915 --> 00:13:40,951
This is more of a monument
to a long dead...

62
00:13:41,127 --> 00:13:43,700
...and extremely powerful civilization.

63
00:13:43,880 --> 00:13:46,548
This is where he learned who he was.

64
00:13:47,049 --> 00:13:49,719
This is where he came for guidance.

65
00:14:00,646 --> 00:14:02,686
Possibilities.

66
00:14:02,857 --> 00:14:06,937
Endless possibilities.

67
00:14:51,907 --> 00:14:54,907
You act like you've been here before.

68
00:15:20,977 --> 00:15:22,804
<i>My son...</i>

69
00:15:25,315 --> 00:15:27,723
<i>... you do not remember me.</i>

70
00:15:28,694 --> 00:15:30,817
<i>I am Jor-El.</i>

71
00:15:31,238 --> 00:15:33,314
<i>I'm your father.</i>

72
00:15:33,491 --> 00:15:37,571
<i>By now, I will have been dead
many thousands of your years.</i>

73
00:15:37,745 --> 00:15:41,244
<i>- He thinks I'm his son.
- You are the only survivor of Krypton.</i>

74
00:15:41,874 --> 00:15:47,081
<i>Embedded in the crystals before you is
the total accumulation of all literature...</i>

75
00:15:47,254 --> 00:15:50,125
<i>... and scientific fact
from dozens of other worlds...</i>

76
00:15:50,299 --> 00:15:53,714
<i>... spanning the 28 known galaxies.</i>

77
00:15:54,219 --> 00:15:56,675
<i>There are questions to be asked.</i>

78
00:15:57,306 --> 00:15:58,966
<i>Here in this...</i>

79
00:15:59,141 --> 00:16:01,632
<i>This Fortress of Solitude...</i>

80
00:16:02,185 --> 00:16:05,685
<i>... we shall try to find
the answers together.</i>

81
00:16:05,856 --> 00:16:07,350
Can he see us?

82
00:16:08,109 --> 00:16:09,733
No, he's dead.

83
00:16:10,944 --> 00:16:12,273
<i>So, my son...</i>

84
00:16:15,866 --> 00:16:17,693
<i>... Kal-El...</i>

85
00:16:21,205 --> 00:16:23,245
<i>... speak.</i>

86
00:16:24,917 --> 00:16:26,874
Tell me everything...

87
00:16:27,044 --> 00:16:29,666
...starting with crystals.

88
00:19:26,517 --> 00:19:27,975
Hey, boy.

89
00:19:54,086 --> 00:19:56,079
<i>- On Tuesday, between support...</i>

90
00:19:56,255 --> 00:19:58,580
<i>- hindered the firefighting efforts
for all those...</i>

91
00:19:58,758 --> 00:20:03,420
<i>Police have finally arrived and it's
still complete mayhem down here.</i>

92
00:20:04,805 --> 00:20:07,177
<i>Fighting broke out in the
southernmost region...</i>

93
00:20:07,350 --> 00:20:09,757
<i>... with border fire
and small-arms attacks prevalent.</i>

94
00:20:09,936 --> 00:20:11,679
Don't worry, I buried it this morning.

95
00:20:11,854 --> 00:20:14,939
<i>- It was futile trying to force him
to testify before a grand jury.</i>

96
00:20:15,108 --> 00:20:16,602
Mom?

97
00:20:18,027 --> 00:20:20,019
Five years.

98
00:20:21,947 --> 00:20:25,317
If your father was alive,
he never would have let you go.

99
00:20:26,036 --> 00:20:27,613
I almost gave up hope.

100
00:20:27,787 --> 00:20:31,037
I just thought
I would never see you again.

101
00:20:31,791 --> 00:20:34,365
Oh, Clark.

102
00:20:41,634 --> 00:20:44,304
Did you find what you were looking for?

103
00:20:45,138 --> 00:20:48,838
I thought, hoped...

104
00:20:49,684 --> 00:20:51,476
...it might still be there.

105
00:20:52,187 --> 00:20:53,978
Your home?

106
00:20:56,483 --> 00:20:58,808
That place was a graveyard.

107
00:21:00,278 --> 00:21:01,737
I'm all that's left.

108
00:21:03,990 --> 00:21:07,526
Clark, the universe is a big place.

109
00:21:08,077 --> 00:21:10,319
And you don't know who's out there.

110
00:21:12,123 --> 00:21:14,579
And even if you are the last...

111
00:21:17,170 --> 00:21:18,997
...you're not alone.

112
00:21:23,844 --> 00:21:25,421
I know.

113
00:21:47,033 --> 00:21:48,196
- Sorry.
- Look out!

114
00:21:48,369 --> 00:21:49,613
Watch out, will you?

115
00:21:49,786 --> 00:21:51,281
- Excuse me.
- Sorry.

116
00:21:52,873 --> 00:21:54,201
Sorry.

117
00:21:55,709 --> 00:21:58,710
Great. Would you be careful?

118
00:21:59,713 --> 00:22:03,212
- Jimmy.
- Mr. Clark! I mean, Kent! Mr. Kent!

119
00:22:03,384 --> 00:22:05,460
Welcome back! Oh, my God!

120
00:22:05,636 --> 00:22:09,384
Hey, come... Wait right there.
I'll be right back.

121
00:22:18,858 --> 00:22:22,309
Oh, hey, sorry, guys,
I'm still looking for a place to live...

122
00:22:22,486 --> 00:22:24,229
...if you know of anything reasonable.

123
00:22:24,404 --> 00:22:28,070
Behind you, Mr. Kent.
I made it myself. It's a cake.

124
00:22:29,952 --> 00:22:31,446
Oh, it looks...

125
00:22:32,497 --> 00:22:33,694
...delicious.

126
00:22:33,873 --> 00:22:38,202
Olsen! Where are the photos
of that birthday-clown-massacre thing?

127
00:22:38,377 --> 00:22:40,951
I'm on it, chief. Hey, look who's back.

128
00:22:41,381 --> 00:22:42,756
- Kent?
- Hey, chief.

129
00:22:42,924 --> 00:22:45,415
- Thank you for giving me my job back.
- Don't thank me.

130
00:22:45,593 --> 00:22:46,921
Thank Norm Palmer for dying.

131
00:22:48,804 --> 00:22:50,761
It was his time.

132
00:22:52,058 --> 00:22:55,640
- Let's get you set up, huh?
- Olsen!

133
00:22:55,811 --> 00:22:57,056
Okay, so I gotta run...

134
00:22:57,229 --> 00:23:00,515
...but I will be back to check on you
in a sec, Mr. Kent.

135
00:23:00,692 --> 00:23:04,855
Oh, hey, do you know
where I can find Lois?

136
00:23:18,792 --> 00:23:21,165
<i>The timing of this
automated-ignition countdown...</i>

137
00:23:21,337 --> 00:23:23,495
<i>... is the most precarious part
of the launch.</i>

138
00:23:23,923 --> 00:23:25,298
<i>Lois Lane, Daily Planet.</i>

139
00:23:25,466 --> 00:23:28,717
<i>You also stated that the shuttle
will usher in a new era of travel...</i>

140
00:23:28,887 --> 00:23:31,922
<i>... enabling the average person
to afford transcontinental flights.</i>

141
00:23:32,098 --> 00:23:34,174
<i>But can you tell us the exact price...</i>

142
00:23:34,350 --> 00:23:36,924
<i>... an "average person"
will be expected to pay?</i>

143
00:23:37,145 --> 00:23:39,814
<i>The answer to that question
is in your press packet.</i>

144
00:23:39,981 --> 00:23:42,732
<i>The Earth is surrounded
by a blanket of air...</i>

145
00:23:42,900 --> 00:23:45,272
<i>... which we call the atmosphere.</i>

146
00:23:45,445 --> 00:23:49,028
<i>It reaches over...</i>

147
00:24:35,079 --> 00:24:37,865
Yeah. He looks just like his mom.

148
00:24:38,039 --> 00:24:42,037
Already takes after her too, especially
when it comes to getting into trouble.

149
00:24:42,210 --> 00:24:43,705
Mother?

150
00:24:45,547 --> 00:24:50,210
Oh, yeah, well, I guess you've been gone.
Fearless reporter Lois Lane is a mommy.

151
00:24:52,555 --> 00:24:55,840
Oh, you know, I'll just...
I'll take that. That's good.

152
00:24:56,016 --> 00:24:58,934
- Sorry.
- No. She's got plenty.

153
00:24:59,103 --> 00:25:01,060
- Wait, she's married?
- Yes.

154
00:25:01,563 --> 00:25:05,608
No. Not really. It's more like
a prolonged engagement.

155
00:25:05,775 --> 00:25:08,231
But don't ask Miss Lane
when they're tying the knot...

156
00:25:08,403 --> 00:25:11,939
...because she hates that question.

157
00:25:12,116 --> 00:25:16,577
<i>- Like this follow the same stringent
safety guidelines set by NASA?</i>

158
00:25:16,745 --> 00:25:19,366
<i>Since this is a joint venture
with the Air Force...</i>

159
00:25:19,540 --> 00:25:23,040
You all right? You look like
you could use a drink.

160
00:25:25,462 --> 00:25:28,713
This place is so tacky.
Why are we back here?

161
00:25:28,883 --> 00:25:32,501
Kitty, while you were doing your nails
and ordering fur coats online...

162
00:25:32,678 --> 00:25:34,421
...I was busy unlocking the secrets...

163
00:25:34,596 --> 00:25:37,467
...of one of the most advanced
civilizations in the universe.

164
00:25:37,642 --> 00:25:38,886
Weren't there two of those?

165
00:25:39,059 --> 00:25:43,306
You see, unlike our clunky
earthbound forms of construction...

166
00:25:43,480 --> 00:25:45,936
...the technology on Krypton,
Superman's home world...

167
00:25:46,108 --> 00:25:48,516
...was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.

168
00:25:48,694 --> 00:25:50,069
Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.

169
00:25:50,237 --> 00:25:53,986
Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...

170
00:25:54,158 --> 00:25:56,281
...would be indistinguishable from magic.

171
00:25:56,452 --> 00:26:00,829
But imagine: Cities, vehicles, weapons...

172
00:26:01,415 --> 00:26:03,040
...entire continents...

173
00:26:03,376 --> 00:26:06,128
...all grown.

174
00:26:13,803 --> 00:26:17,137
To think that one could create
a new world...

175
00:26:17,307 --> 00:26:20,307
...with such a simple little object.

176
00:26:22,020 --> 00:26:24,308
It's like a seed.

177
00:26:24,480 --> 00:26:26,722
And all it needs is water.

178
00:26:26,899 --> 00:26:28,359
Like...

179
00:26:29,151 --> 00:26:31,144
...Sea-Monkeys.

180
00:26:32,822 --> 00:26:35,111
Exactly, Kitty.

181
00:26:35,658 --> 00:26:37,319
Like Sea-Monkeys.

182
00:26:39,538 --> 00:26:44,115
Clark has been doing a little
soul-searching for the last couple years.

183
00:26:44,292 --> 00:26:46,284
- He saw Ilamas.
- Yeah?

184
00:26:46,460 --> 00:26:48,500
- Yeah.
- Must be tough coming back.

185
00:26:50,215 --> 00:26:52,373
- Coming back?
- To work.

186
00:26:53,301 --> 00:26:54,760
Yeah.

187
00:26:55,178 --> 00:26:57,751
Well, you know, things change.

188
00:26:57,931 --> 00:26:59,970
I mean, of course things change...

189
00:27:00,141 --> 00:27:06,013
...but sometimes things that you didn't
think would change could change.

190
00:27:06,481 --> 00:27:08,058
Take Lois.

191
00:27:08,232 --> 00:27:12,183
A woman like her,
I never thought she'd settle down.

192
00:27:12,654 --> 00:27:16,319
You know, if you ask me...
Because she'll never tell you this...

193
00:27:16,492 --> 00:27:21,366
...but if you ask me,
she's still in love with you-know-who.

194
00:27:29,713 --> 00:27:33,580
The original space shuttle
generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust...

195
00:27:33,759 --> 00:27:35,467
...just in the initial launch phase.

196
00:27:35,636 --> 00:27:40,381
But, by piggybacking
on this Boeing 777... Yes?

197
00:27:40,558 --> 00:27:42,597
If this launch is as pivotal as you claim...

198
00:27:42,768 --> 00:27:45,057
...why is it being covered
by one news network?

199
00:27:45,228 --> 00:27:48,432
Why don't we save those questions
for the post-launch briefing.

200
00:27:48,607 --> 00:27:50,231
How about that, Miss Lane?

201
00:27:50,400 --> 00:27:53,851
When we hit 40,000 feet,
the shuttle will detach, ascend...

202
00:27:54,029 --> 00:27:57,730
...and then fire the first of two propellant
systems, the liquid fuel boosters.

203
00:27:57,908 --> 00:27:59,948
When the shuttle
reaches the stratosphere...

204
00:28:00,119 --> 00:28:02,242
...the secondary
insertion booster will fire...

205
00:28:02,413 --> 00:28:05,781
...propelling the craft
at 4gs into the mesosphere.

206
00:28:09,628 --> 00:28:11,786
- Careful.
- I know.

207
00:28:12,631 --> 00:28:15,633
- Careful. Careful.
- I know.

208
00:28:42,870 --> 00:28:45,326
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

209
00:28:45,498 --> 00:28:47,787
Wait for it.

210
00:28:51,211 --> 00:28:53,963
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

211
00:28:56,425 --> 00:28:59,131
<i>It's freaking Gone With the Wind.</i>

212
00:28:59,803 --> 00:29:01,843
- Shut off the camera.
- But I'm getting it.

213
00:29:02,014 --> 00:29:04,053
I said, shut off the damn camera.

214
00:29:10,439 --> 00:29:12,148
I think I did something wrong.

215
00:29:12,317 --> 00:29:16,646
No. That wasn't you.

216
00:29:44,224 --> 00:29:47,888
<i>Ignition is at T minus one minute
and we are prepping for separation.</i>

217
00:29:48,061 --> 00:29:49,555
CDR, start the clock.

218
00:29:50,188 --> 00:29:52,513
<i>Three minutes and counting.</i>

219
00:29:52,690 --> 00:29:54,932
<i>Body signs normal. Crew is looking good.</i>

220
00:29:55,110 --> 00:29:56,769
Shuttle readouts are holding steady.

221
00:29:56,945 --> 00:29:59,186
<i>- We're still a go for launch.
- Roger.</i>

222
00:30:06,705 --> 00:30:09,575
<i>- Houston, you copy?
- Houston, do you copy?</i>

223
00:30:13,545 --> 00:30:14,576
Oh, God.

224
00:30:16,047 --> 00:30:17,791
<i>Electrical variance.</i>

225
00:30:21,595 --> 00:30:23,137
What the...?

226
00:30:30,020 --> 00:30:32,059
Please, there's nothing to worry about.

227
00:30:32,230 --> 00:30:36,477
It seems that we are experiencing
a slight power outage.

228
00:30:40,447 --> 00:30:43,899
- What did you do?
- It wasn't me. It just cycled back up.

229
00:30:45,452 --> 00:30:47,112
<i>Genesis, radio check from Houston.</i>

230
00:30:48,747 --> 00:30:51,238
There we have it.
We were experiencing a power outage.

231
00:30:53,668 --> 00:30:56,242
<i>- Climbing to 40,000 feet.
- Roger, 40,000 feet.</i>

232
00:31:07,766 --> 00:31:10,435
<i>And it's gone! A blazing fastball...</i>

233
00:31:31,916 --> 00:31:33,114
Is that it?

234
00:31:39,339 --> 00:31:41,665
I don't think so.

235
00:32:31,142 --> 00:32:33,597
<i>Dual engine failure,
but they're up and running again.</i>

236
00:32:33,769 --> 00:32:37,638
<i>Genesis, I hate to say this, but it looks
like we're gonna have to scrub the launch.</i>

237
00:32:37,815 --> 00:32:41,350
- Aborting booster ignition.
- Roger. Aborting booster ignition.

238
00:32:43,071 --> 00:32:46,321
Boosters are non-responsive.
We're still counting down for ignition.

239
00:32:46,490 --> 00:32:48,199
<i>- Platform, we have a problem.
- Go.</i>

240
00:32:48,368 --> 00:32:50,776
<i>Looks like something faulted
during the power outage.</i>

241
00:32:50,953 --> 00:32:53,278
<i>Both boosters are
counting down for ignition.</i>

242
