01:01:47,706 --> 01:01:50,957
<i>Reports are flooding in from Metropolis,
Houston, Gotham and as far...</i>

478
01:01:51,127 --> 01:01:53,878
<i>Satellites have proven
most ineffective at tracking him.</i>

479
01:01:54,046 --> 01:01:57,581
<i>He might literally be moving
near the speed of light.</i>

480
01:02:10,813 --> 01:02:13,683
<i>- Our map is illuminated with sightings...
- Kent!</i>

481
01:02:13,857 --> 01:02:16,894
<i>- The chief is waiting.
- ... on every continent, giving citizens...</i>

482
01:02:20,781 --> 01:02:24,481
These are iconic, and they were taken
by a 12-year-old with a camera phone.

483
01:02:24,660 --> 01:02:27,827
- What do you got, Olsen?
- I got those.

484
01:02:30,083 --> 01:02:31,826
- Look, in the sky, chief.
- It's a bird.

485
01:02:32,001 --> 01:02:33,578
- It's a plane.
- No, look, it's...

486
01:02:34,337 --> 01:02:35,534
You wanted to see me?

487
01:02:36,464 --> 01:02:38,172
Yeah, Kent, come on in. Sit down.

488
01:02:38,341 --> 01:02:41,342
I wanna talk a little strategy. Okay.

489
01:02:41,844 --> 01:02:44,513
First off, Lois, I don't understand
what you're doing...

490
01:02:44,680 --> 01:02:47,966
...sneaking around covering the blackout.
- It wasn't just a blackout.

491
01:02:48,143 --> 01:02:50,135
Cell phones, pagers,
automobiles, airplane...

492
01:02:50,312 --> 01:02:52,766
Every other paper in town
has got a female reporter...

493
01:02:52,938 --> 01:02:56,355
...a good-looking female reporter,
stashed on the roof covering Superman.

494
01:02:56,526 --> 01:03:00,191
- And you two are the ones with history.
- Chief, I've done Superman.

495
01:03:01,864 --> 01:03:03,904
Covered him. You know what I mean.

496
01:03:04,075 --> 01:03:06,233
Yeah, that makes you an expert.
Do him again.

497
01:03:06,410 --> 01:03:09,198
- There are a dozen other stories out there.
- Yeah? Name one.

498
01:03:09,372 --> 01:03:11,946
Well, there was a museum robbery
last night.

499
01:03:12,458 --> 01:03:15,910
Even Superman missed that one.
He was too busy saving this hooker.

500
01:03:16,087 --> 01:03:18,756
Why don't you guys
track down Lex Luthor?

501
01:03:19,465 --> 01:03:21,707
Well, no one's seen him
since his fifth appeal.

502
01:03:21,884 --> 01:03:24,043
He's got more history
with Superman than anyone.

503
01:03:24,220 --> 01:03:25,714
Maybe he's got something to say.

504
01:03:25,888 --> 01:03:29,638
- Luthor's yesterday's news.
- No, I like that idea.

505
01:03:30,602 --> 01:03:35,145
Perry, Lex Luthor is a career criminal
who nearly killed him, for God's sakes.

506
01:03:35,315 --> 01:03:37,557
Jimmy, how did Lex Luthor
get out of prison?

507
01:03:37,734 --> 01:03:41,732
Well, the appeals court called Superman
as a witness and he wasn't around.

508
01:03:42,447 --> 01:03:44,570
How much do you think
that pisses off Superman?

509
01:03:44,741 --> 01:03:46,366
- Give him to someone else.
- A lot.

510
01:03:46,535 --> 01:03:48,444
- A lot.
- Polly. Give him to Polly.

511
01:03:53,584 --> 01:03:55,126
Lois, Superman.

512
01:03:55,294 --> 01:03:57,500
- What about the blackout?
- Kent, blackout.

513
01:04:00,090 --> 01:04:02,416
Great. Thanks, chief.

514
01:04:05,554 --> 01:04:10,382
Lois, I'm sorry. I'd hate if this
damaged our relationship.

515
01:04:11,726 --> 01:04:12,841
Relationship?

516
01:04:13,603 --> 01:04:15,014
- Yeah.
- Hi, Mommy.

517
01:04:15,189 --> 01:04:17,062
- Hi, you.
- Hey, guys.

518
01:04:17,232 --> 01:04:21,016
He got an A in science, but a D in gym,
so we're doing something right.

519
01:04:21,195 --> 01:04:23,187
- Yeah, at least one of us is.
- What?

520
01:04:23,363 --> 01:04:26,199
It's Perry. He just shoved Superman
back into my life.

521
01:04:26,367 --> 01:04:29,320
Well, honey, I'm sure you can
find a way to interview Superman...

522
01:04:29,494 --> 01:04:31,487
...without bringing him
back into your life.

523
01:04:31,663 --> 01:04:35,957
<i>There's really no way around it, folks.
Superman is back in all of our lives.</i>

524
01:04:37,419 --> 01:04:39,211
<i>We're coming to you from Sydney...</i>

525
01:04:39,380 --> 01:04:43,164
<i>... where people have gathered
on these rooftops to scour the sky...</i>

526
01:04:43,342 --> 01:04:46,545
Okay, how about this?
We'll stay late. We'll get dinner.

527
01:04:46,720 --> 01:04:50,339
I'll help with Superman, and you and
Clark can work on the blackout together.

528
01:04:50,515 --> 01:04:53,470
- Is that all right with you, Clark?
- Swell.

529
01:05:17,376 --> 01:05:21,420
I was gonna pretend
the brakes were out.

530
01:05:21,588 --> 01:05:24,709
Pretend. Like we talked about.

531
01:05:24,884 --> 01:05:27,670
You didn't actually have to cut them!

532
01:05:27,845 --> 01:05:29,126
Of course I did.

533
01:05:29,305 --> 01:05:34,133
A man can always tell when a woman
is pretending, especially Superman.

534
01:05:39,023 --> 01:05:41,395
So did you get your rock?

535
01:05:42,777 --> 01:05:44,686
I did.

536
01:05:46,072 --> 01:05:50,116
<i>U.S. Coast Guard issuing a small-craft
advisory for the Metropolis ocean area.</i>

537
01:05:50,284 --> 01:05:52,111
<i>High-wind advisory is in effect...</i>

538
01:05:52,286 --> 01:05:55,157
<i>... ocean currents and tides
becoming increasingly dangerous.</i>

539
01:05:55,331 --> 01:05:58,534
<i>All warnings lasting
until later this evening.</i>

540
01:05:58,709 --> 01:05:59,955
<i>Security, security.</i>

541
01:06:00,128 --> 01:06:05,584
<i>This is U.S. Coast Guard issuing
a small-craft advisory for northeast seas.</i>

542
01:06:05,758 --> 01:06:10,219
<i>Winds reaching 50 miles per hour,
high tides in the morning.</i>

543
01:06:10,388 --> 01:06:12,215
<i>Waves reaching 20 to 30 feet.</i>

544
01:06:12,390 --> 01:06:16,388
<i>This warning is in effect for
all small crafts for the next four hours.</i>

545
01:06:40,502 --> 01:06:42,126
Weird. If these times are right...

546
01:06:42,295 --> 01:06:45,380
...the blackout spread
from a specific origin point.

547
01:06:45,549 --> 01:06:46,924
Where?

548
01:06:47,092 --> 01:06:48,883
I'm not sure yet.

549
01:06:49,594 --> 01:06:53,259
With the super-hearing, does he hear each
sound by itself or everything at once?

550
01:06:53,640 --> 01:06:54,885
<i>Both.</i>

551
01:06:55,058 --> 01:06:57,264
<i>- He's certainly taller than I thought.
- 6'4".</i>

552
01:06:57,435 --> 01:07:01,184
I love that he can see through anything.
I'd have fun with that.

553
01:07:01,564 --> 01:07:03,273
<i>Anything but lead.</i>

554
01:07:06,528 --> 01:07:07,773
- I bet he's...
- 225 pounds...

555
01:07:07,946 --> 01:07:09,606
...faster than a speeding bullet...

556
01:07:09,782 --> 01:07:13,232
...draws his power from the sun,
invulnerable to anything but kryptonite...

557
01:07:13,410 --> 01:07:15,449
...and he never lies.
- Kryptonite?

558
01:07:15,620 --> 01:07:17,946
Radioactive pieces of his home world.

559
01:07:18,123 --> 01:07:20,329
It's deadly. To him.

560
01:07:24,922 --> 01:07:28,290
Lois, how tall would you say Clark is?

561
01:07:29,844 --> 01:07:31,836
<i>About 6'3", 6'4".</i>

562
01:07:32,012 --> 01:07:34,799
<i>About 200, 215 pounds?</i>

563
01:07:44,775 --> 01:07:48,773
Jimmy, Jason, let's go get these intrepid
reporters something to keep them going.

564
01:07:48,946 --> 01:07:50,820
- Burritos!
- Come here, canhead.

565
01:07:52,324 --> 01:07:56,274
We're going this way. Do they have
anything other than burritos?

566
01:07:57,162 --> 01:07:59,488
I think they have fries and burgers.

567
01:07:59,665 --> 01:08:02,156
So have you found a place to live yet?

568
01:08:02,335 --> 01:08:03,912
No. I'm still looking.

569
01:08:04,670 --> 01:08:07,161
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

570
01:08:07,339 --> 01:08:10,839
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

571
01:08:24,606 --> 01:08:26,315
Thanks.

572
01:08:34,116 --> 01:08:36,868
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

573
01:09:30,381 --> 01:09:33,133
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

574
01:09:36,430 --> 01:09:38,920
- Sorry. Didn't mean to startle you.
- I'm fine. Really.

575
01:09:41,058 --> 01:09:44,179
I just wasn't expecting you.

576
01:09:44,855 --> 01:09:46,432
With all the press on the plane...

577
01:09:46,606 --> 01:09:49,014
...I wasn't sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

578
01:09:49,192 --> 01:09:52,359
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

579
01:09:54,572 --> 01:09:57,028
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

580
01:09:57,409 --> 01:10:00,943
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

581
01:10:02,623 --> 01:10:05,956
So you're here for an interview?

582
01:10:07,210 --> 01:10:08,242
Okay, then.

583
01:10:12,132 --> 01:10:14,124
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

584
01:10:20,265 --> 01:10:22,970
Let's start with the big question.

585
01:10:23,143 --> 01:10:25,634
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

586
01:10:25,812 --> 01:10:28,185
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

587
01:10:28,357 --> 01:10:29,815
It was.

588
01:10:29,983 --> 01:10:32,355
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

589
01:10:33,820 --> 01:10:36,192
...I had to see for myself.

590
01:10:39,827 --> 01:10:43,659
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

591
01:10:46,875 --> 01:10:48,334
Not everyone.

592
01:10:49,503 --> 01:10:51,911
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

593
01:10:52,089 --> 01:10:55,043
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

594
01:10:56,719 --> 01:10:58,758
How could you leave us like that?

595
01:11:00,264 --> 01:11:02,671
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

596
01:11:03,184 --> 01:11:04,677
That's why I wrote it.

597
01:11:04,852 --> 01:11:07,639
The world doesn't need a savior.

598
01:11:08,064 --> 01:11:09,973
And neither do I.

599
01:11:25,122 --> 01:11:26,201
Lois.

600
01:11:27,917 --> 01:11:30,372
Will you come with me?

601
01:11:32,130 --> 01:11:33,707
Why?

602
01:11:34,090 --> 01:11:36,213
There's something I wanna show you.

603
01:11:42,473 --> 01:11:44,264
Please.

604
01:11:55,278 --> 01:11:57,436
I can't be gone long.

605
01:11:57,613 --> 01:11:59,522
You won't be.

606
01:12:11,919 --> 01:12:14,671
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

607
01:12:14,839 --> 01:12:17,128
...is because it was
too unbearable for you.

608
01:12:17,300 --> 01:12:19,922
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

609
01:12:20,511 --> 01:12:23,678
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

610
01:12:24,765 --> 01:12:26,889
Maybe Clark's right.

611
01:12:30,271 --> 01:12:32,394
You know, my...

612
01:12:32,565 --> 01:12:37,607
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

613
01:12:38,780 --> 01:12:40,772
Not like this.

614
01:12:55,630 --> 01:12:58,038
I forgot how warm you were.

615
01:13:28,663 --> 01:13:30,158
Listen.

616
01:13:31,041 --> 01:13:32,950
What do you hear?

617
01:13:33,669 --> 01:13:34,913
Nothing.

618
01:13:38,841 --> 01:13:40,584
I hear everything.

619
01:13:44,054 --> 01:13:46,675
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

620
01:13:48,016 --> 01:13:51,350
...but every day
I hear people crying for one.

621
01:14:04,199 --> 01:14:06,869
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

622
01:14:10,748 --> 01:14:12,787
I'll take you back now.

623
01:16:25,926 --> 01:16:27,550
Richard's a good man.

624
01:16:30,973 --> 01:16:33,179
And you've been gone a long time.

625
01:16:35,853 --> 01:16:37,430
I know.

626
01:16:42,193 --> 01:16:43,521
L...

627
01:16:48,741 --> 01:16:50,733
So will I see you around?

628
01:16:51,743 --> 01:16:53,736
I'm always around.

629
01:16:55,039 --> 01:16:56,746
Good night, Lois.

630
01:17:15,726 --> 01:17:19,593
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

631
01:17:23,401 --> 01:17:24,978
You all right?

632
01:17:26,820 --> 01:17:28,232
Where have you been?

633
01:17:32,577 --> 01:17:38,247
I was up on the roof, getting some air.

634
01:17:38,916 --> 01:17:40,874
Tell the truth now.

635
01:17:47,425 --> 01:17:48,587
Were you smoking?

636
01:17:51,220 --> 01:17:52,963
No.

637
01:18:01,772 --> 01:18:02,971
Is this real?

638
01:18:04,025 --> 01:18:05,898
- Where'd you find him?
- He found me.

639
01:18:06,068 --> 01:18:08,856
Oh, this is great. I can't wait to read it.

640
01:18:09,030 --> 01:18:11,438
So, Mr. White, about the blackout...

641
01:18:11,616 --> 01:18:14,107
Lois, this is the biggest night
of your life.

642
01:18:14,285 --> 01:18:16,443
Have you picked out a dress?
Something snazzy?

643
01:18:17,455 --> 01:18:20,160
It just feels a little weird
winning for that article.

644
01:18:20,333 --> 01:18:23,369
- It just doesn't seem right.
- What doesn't seem right?

645
01:18:23,544 --> 01:18:27,128
Winning an award for an article called
"Why the World Doesn't Need Superman."

646
01:18:27,298 --> 01:18:29,753
When, according
to this newspaper, they do.

647
01:18:29,926 --> 01:18:32,843
Lois, Pulitzer Prizes
are like Academy Awards.

648
01:18:33,012 --> 01:18:36,132
Nobody remembers what you got one for.
It's just that you got one.

649
01:18:36,307 --> 01:18:39,427
- But...
- This is your night. You enjoy it.

650
01:18:39,602 --> 01:18:42,141
I'm sure Kent's on the blackout.

651
01:19:42,708 --> 01:19:44,914
Department of Water and Power, please.

652
01:19:45,628 --> 01:19:46,908
7782, great.

653
01:19:48,380 --> 01:19:49,875
Metropolis Public Works.

654
01:19:50,049 --> 01:19:52,539
<i>Hi, Stephen, Lois Lane
from the Daily Planet. Blackout?</i>

655
01:19:52,717 --> 01:19:55,422
I just need a little info
on a few outstanding power grids.

656
01:19:55,596 --> 01:19:57,220
<i>Yeah, I do have it here, actually.</i>

657
01:19:57,389 --> 01:20:01,387
<i>So the uptown grid went dark at 12:36
and midtown 10 seconds before.</i>

658
01:20:01,560 --> 01:20:03,055
Which grid was hit first?

659
01:20:03,229 --> 01:20:04,557
<i>It just reads Vanderworth.</i>

660
01:20:04,730 --> 01:20:07,102
<i>- Across the river?
- 6 Springwood Drive.</i>

661
01:20:07,274 --> 01:20:09,516
6 Springwood Drive.
A residence or a business?

662
01:20:09,694 --> 01:20:11,437
<i>- Residence.
- Sure? Nothing before that?</i>

663
01:20:11,612 --> 01:20:13,937
<i>- That's all it shows.
- Thank you very much.</i>

664
01:20:15,783 --> 01:20:17,063
Oh, Jason.

665
01:20:23,874 --> 01:20:27,078
- There's your mom, Jason.
- You're late, Mommy.

666
01:20:35,303 --> 01:20:38,138
Where are we? Is this the Pulitzer?

667
01:20:38,305 --> 01:20:42,600
Nope. I've just gotta ask these people
a few questions and then we can go.

668
01:20:56,908 --> 01:20:59,280
Can I stay in the car?

669
01:20:59,828 --> 01:21:01,405
No, honey.

670
01:21:08,086 --> 01:21:12,463
- Are we trespassing?
- No. Yes.

671
01:21:27,188 --> 01:21:29,015
Hello?

672
01:22:00,514 --> 01:22:02,055
Hello?

673
01:22:13,151 --> 01:22:15,725
I like the curly one.

674
01:22:23,037 --> 01:22:25,871
Let's go. This was a bad idea.

675
01:22:41,596 --> 01:22:43,388
Lex Luthor.

676
01:22:45,392 --> 01:22:47,515
Lois Lane?

677
01:22:53,317 --> 01:22:54,645
You're bald.

678
01:23:14,755 --> 01:23:16,130
And what is your name?

679
01:23:16,298 --> 01:23:18,754
I'm not supposed to talk to strangers.

680
01:23:19,260 --> 01:23:21,217
- Cute kid, and smart.
- Thanks.

681
01:23:21,387 --> 01:23:24,590
We're not really strangers, are we?
This is kind of a little reunion.

682
01:23:24,765 --> 01:23:26,804
Heck, I'm a fan.

683
01:23:26,975 --> 01:23:28,470
I love your writing...

684
01:23:29,311 --> 01:23:31,138
...and your dress.
- I love your boat.

685
01:23:31,313 --> 01:23:33,935
How'd you get it?
Swindle some widow out of her money?

686
01:23:35,275 --> 01:23:37,517
That's funny. Didn't you win
the Pulitzer Prize...

687
01:23:37,694 --> 01:23:41,278
...for my favorite article of all time, " Why
the World Doesn't Need Superman"?

688
01:23:41,449 --> 01:23:45,363
Didn't you have a few more years to go
on that double life sentence?

689
01:23:45,536 --> 01:23:47,778
Yes, well, we can thank
the Man of Steel for that.

690
01:23:47,955 --> 01:23:51,241
I mean, he's really good at swooping in
and catching the bad guys...

691
01:23:51,417 --> 01:23:54,951
...but he's not so hot at the little things,
like Miranda rights...

692
01:23:55,129 --> 01:23:59,838
...due process, making your court date.

693
01:24:00,009 --> 01:24:02,465
Did you have anything to do
with the blackout?

694
01:24:05,473 --> 01:24:07,680
Are you fishing for an interview,
Miss Lane?

695
01:24:07,851 --> 01:24:10,009
It's been a while
since you've been a headline.

696
01:24:10,185 --> 01:24:12,344
Maybe it's time
people knew your name again.

697
01:24:13,022 --> 01:24:16,972
How about we turn this boat around,
call a cab for my son...

698
01:24:17,527 --> 01:24:20,148
...and then you can do
whatever you want with me.

699
01:24:20,864 --> 01:24:23,401
No, I don't think we'll be
turning around, Miss Lane...

700
01:24:23,574 --> 01:24:26,196
...which means that
we do have some time to kill.

701
01:24:28,371 --> 01:24:30,244
How about that interview?

702
01:24:31,166 --> 01:24:34,499
Yeah, just call me if you hear anything.
Okay. Thank you.

703
01:24:34,669 --> 01:24:36,376
So, what did the school say?

704
01:24:36,545 --> 01:24:38,040
She picked him up at 3: 15.

705
01:24:42,302 --> 01:24:45,587
- Hi, I heard about Lois.
- Yes, come in, Clark, come in.

706
01:24:45,763 --> 01:24:48,254
- Is there anything I can do?
- Yeah, you're a reporter.

707
01:24:48,433 --> 01:24:51,185
- Help Richard track her down.
- I'll check her computer.

708
01:24:51,353 --> 01:24:52,597
Excuse me, Clark.

709
01:25:06,326 --> 01:25:09,410
What do you know about crystals?

710
01:25:09,579 --> 01:25:11,287
They make great chandeliers.

711
01:25:11,873 --> 01:25:16,868
This crystal may seem unremarkable,
but so is the seed of a redwood tree.

712
01:25:17,045 --> 01:25:20,461
It's how our mutual friend in tights
made his Arctic getaway spot.

713
01:25:20,632 --> 01:25:22,505
Cute. It's a little small for my taste.

714
01:25:22,675 --> 01:25:24,218
You're building an island?

715
01:25:25,428 --> 01:25:28,762
You're not seeing
the big picture here, Miss Lane.

716
01:25:28,932 --> 01:25:31,220
Let me enlarge it for you.

717
01:25:33,812 --> 01:25:37,228
Not just an island,
an entirely new continent.

718
01:25:37,399 --> 01:25:40,649
An extinct world, reborn on our own.

719
01:25:40,819 --> 01:25:42,229
Why?

720
01:25:45,240 --> 01:25:47,149
Land, Miss Lane.

721
01:25:47,326 --> 01:25:50,078
I mean... Kitty, what did my father
used to say to me?

722
01:25:50,246 --> 01:25:51,656
"You're losing your hair"?

723
01:25:52,665 --> 01:25:54,574
- Before that.
- "Get out"?

724
01:25:56,126 --> 01:25:58,415
He said, " You can print money...

725
01:25:58,587 --> 01:26:01,209
...manufacture diamonds,
and people are a dime a dozen...

726
01:26:01,382 --> 01:26:04,466
...but they'll always need land."

727
01:26:04,635 --> 01:26:07,470
It's the one thing
they're not making any more of.

728
01:26:08,014 --> 01:26:10,385
But the United States...

729
01:26:12,101 --> 01:26:15,600
Will be underwater.

730
01:26:16,021 --> 01:26:17,599
It's simple physics, Miss Lane.

731
01:26:17,773 --> 01:26:20,560
Two objects cannot occupy
the same space at the same time.

732
01:26:20,735 --> 01:26:23,273
And the rest of the world
will just let you keep it?

733
01:26:23,445 --> 01:26:25,651
- They'll...
- Theyll...

734
01:26:26,156 --> 01:26:27,616
...what?

735
01:26:27,783 --> 01:26:30,654
I'll have advanced alien technology...

736
01:26:30,828 --> 01:26:33,865
...thousands of years beyond
what anyone could throw at me.

737
01:26:34,040 --> 01:26:36,079
Bring it on!

738
01:26:37,084 --> 01:26:38,993
And eventually...

739
01:26:39,169 --> 01:26:41,495
...the rest of the world
will be begging me...

740
01:26:41,672 --> 01:26:44,294
...for a piece of high-tech
beachfront property.

741
01:26:44,467 --> 01:26:46,792
In fact, they'll pay
through the nose for it.

742
01:26:47,220 --> 01:26:48,963
But millions of people will die.

743
01:26:49,138 --> 01:26:51,759
Billions! Once again,
the press underestimates me.

744
01:26:51,932 --> 01:26:54,304
This is front-page news.

745
01:26:54,977 --> 01:26:56,970
Come on, let me hear you say it
just once.

746
01:26:57,146 --> 01:27:01,642
- You're insane.
- No! Not that. No, the other thing.

747
01:27:01,818 --> 01:27:05,482
It's dangling off the tip of your tongue.
Let me hear it just once, please?

748
01:27:05,655 --> 01:27:08,656
- Superman will never...
- Wrong!

749
01:27:21,880 --> 01:27:23,504
What is that?

750
01:27:24,715 --> 01:27:27,503
I think you know exactly what this is.

751
01:27:33,516 --> 01:27:36,387
Mind over muscle, Miss Lane.

752
01:27:37,521 --> 01:27:39,312
Mind...

753
01:27:46,863 --> 01:27:48,855
Who is that boy's father?

754
01:27:50,367 --> 01:27:52,240
Richard.

755
01:27:52,703 --> 01:27:56,201
<i>Mr. Luthor, we're approaching
the coordinates.</i>

756
01:27:56,790 --> 01:27:58,367
Are you sure?

757
01:27:58,541 --> 01:28:03,880
<i>Yes, sir. Latitude 40 degrees north,
longitude 73 degrees west.</i>

758
01:28:25,402 --> 01:28:27,561
Don't let them leave this room.

759
01:28:27,904 --> 01:28:30,477
Kitty, come with me.
You're not gonna want to miss this.

760
01:29:43,564 --> 01:29:44,939
- Damn it.
- What?

761
01:29:45,107 --> 01:29:46,306
She has a password.

762
01:29:48,319 --> 01:29:49,896
"Jason."

763
01:29:51,989 --> 01:29:53,697
"Richard."

764
01:29:55,618 --> 01:29:57,196
Try "Superman."

765
01:30:02,333 --> 01:30:04,740
"Superman." Great.

766
01:30:13,093 --> 01:30:15,169
Don't touch that, honey.

767
01:30:19,433 --> 01:30:21,889
Why don't you go play the piano.

768
01:32:19,138 --> 01:32:21,628
Come on, come on, come on.

769
01:34:08,706 --> 01:34:11,743
Lex, this isn't like the train set.

770
01:34:13,670 --> 01:34:15,413
I know.

771
01:34:21,470 --> 01:34:23,261
Come on, come on.

772
01:34:23,888 --> 01:34:25,087
Come on.

773
01:35:53,021 --> 01:35:54,894
- Honey, are you okay?
- Yeah.

774
01:35:55,064 --> 01:35:57,057
- Are you hurt?
- I'm fine.

775
01:35:58,275 --> 01:36:01,027
Open this door! Open it!

776
01:36:16,377 --> 01:36:18,749
Could you help Mommy open the door?

777
01:36:21,633 --> 01:36:23,376
I'm sorry.

778
01:36:26,470 --> 01:36:28,546
It's gonna be okay.

779
01:36:28,723 --> 01:36:31,048
Okay? It's gonna be okay.

780
01:36:50,745 --> 01:36:54,197
We had a little problem downstairs.

781
01:36:54,749 --> 01:36:56,907
Brutus is dead.

782
01:36:57,585 --> 01:37:00,836
He got hit with the piano.

783
01:37:05,426 --> 01:37:07,301
Where's the boy?

784
01:37:07,471 --> 01:37:11,599
With the mother,
locked up in the pantry.

785
01:37:13,769 --> 01:37:15,927
Oh, it's time for us to go.

786
01:37:21,943 --> 01:37:24,434
My camera's not working.

787
01:37:25,238 --> 01:37:27,361
And my phone's not working.

788
01:37:32,412 --> 01:37:35,164
- Okay, I'm good.
- That was weird.

789
01:37:50,138 --> 01:37:52,464
Hey, guys.
This just came through the fax.

790
01:37:52,641 --> 01:37:54,930
It's Lois' handwriting,
I'd recognize it anywhere.

791
01:37:55,102 --> 01:37:56,929
I just... No idea
what the numbers mean.

792
01:37:57,104 --> 01:37:58,847
- They're coordinates.
- Coordinates.

793
01:38:00,983 --> 01:38:02,180
That's just off the coast.

794
01:38:02,359 --> 01:38:05,479
Jimmy, tell Perry I'm taking the seaplane.
Keep trying her cell.

795
01:40:09,654 --> 01:40:11,112
What are these, lottery numbers?

796
01:40:11,656 --> 01:40:13,648
I think they're coordinates, chief.

797
01:40:52,364 --> 01:40:53,526
Chief...

798
01:41:20,434 --> 01:41:22,723
Come on! Move it!

799
01:43:46,415 --> 01:43:48,158
Chief!

800
01:43:59,303 --> 01:44:01,710
Great Caesar's ghost.

801
01:46:08,683 --> 01:46:10,806
- Daddy.
- Oh, my God.

802
01:46:24,408 --> 01:46:25,818
How did you get here?

803
01:46:25,992 --> 01:46:27,652
I flew.

804
01:46:31,331 --> 01:46:33,158
Look out!

805
01:46:46,013 --> 01:46:47,721
Mom!

806
01:46:47,890 --> 01:46:50,012
Mom! Mom!

807
01:46:50,184 --> 01:46:51,559
Jason, come here! Jason!

808
01:46:54,438 --> 01:46:56,347
Come here! Watch your head!
Come here!

809
01:47:56,875 --> 01:47:58,667
Mommy! Mom!

810
01:48:00,587 --> 01:48:01,833
Jason!

811
01:48:05,300 --> 01:48:06,795
Jason, hold on!

812
01:48:09,930 --> 01:48:12,600
- Have you got him?
- I got him! Go!

813
01:48:15,019 --> 01:48:16,596
Hold on! Hold on!

814
01:48:31,327 --> 01:48:32,656
- Mommy!
- Give him to me!

815
01:48:32,829 --> 01:48:34,406
Mommy!

816
01:48:35,039 --> 01:48:36,948
- Mommy! Mommy!
- Come on, Jason! Come on!

817
01:48:40,795 --> 01:48:43,630
- Lois! Lois!
- Mommy!

818
01:49:48,113 --> 01:49:50,189
Jason, get on my back.

819
01:50:20,229 --> 01:50:21,889
Give me your hand.

820
01:50:29,321 --> 01:50:31,609
- Have you got them?
- Yeah.

821
01:50:50,718 --> 01:50:52,627
Get buckled in!

822
01:51:11,655 --> 01:51:13,529
She'll be fine.

823
01:51:16,285 --> 01:51:17,660
I can't take off in this.

824
01:51:17,828 --> 01:51:21,778
- I'll point you in the right direction.
- Thank you.

825
01:52:21,059 --> 01:52:22,850
See anything familiar?

826
01:52:28,859 --> 01:52:31,266
I see an old man's sick joke.

827
01:52:31,778 --> 01:52:35,194
Really? Because I see
my new apartment...

828
01:52:35,365 --> 01:52:38,401
...and a place for Kitty,
one for my friends...

829
01:52:38,576 --> 01:52:41,531
...and that place over there, I'll rent out.

830
01:52:46,043 --> 01:52:50,254
But, you know, maybe you're right.
You know, maybe it is a little cold.

831
01:52:50,422 --> 01:52:54,372
It's... What's the word I'm searching for?
It's a little...

832
01:52:55,010 --> 01:52:56,718
...alien.

833
01:52:57,720 --> 01:53:01,553
It lacks that human touch.

834
01:53:04,519 --> 01:53:07,224
You have something that belongs to me.

835
01:53:24,748 --> 01:53:28,034
Metropolis Tower, this is seaplane
November-Seven-Two-Four-One-Hotel.

836
01:53:28,209 --> 01:53:29,788
Do you copy?

837
01:53:30,629 --> 01:53:34,129
Metropolis Tower, this is seaplane
November-Seven-Two-Four-One-Hotel.

838
01:53:34,300 --> 01:53:36,625
Do you copy? Damn it!

839
01:53:36,802 --> 01:53:40,420
Metropolis Tower, this is seaplane
November-Seven-Two-Four-One-Hotel.

840
01:53:40,598 --> 01:53:42,424
Do you copy?

841
01:53:44,309 --> 01:53:46,979
Lois! Are you all right?

842
01:53:47,396 --> 01:53:50,765
Yeah. What happened?

843
01:53:51,901 --> 01:53:54,521
- Superman.
- Where is he?

844
01:53:56,030 --> 01:53:57,275
He went back.

845
01:53:59,909 --> 01:54:02,115
- Richard, we have to turn around.
- What? No.

846
01:54:02,286 --> 01:54:04,908
- We have to turn around!
- We barely made it out of there.

847
01:54:05,081 --> 01:54:07,653
- Now you want me to go back?
- Yes, please!

848
01:54:08,417 --> 01:54:10,244
He'll die.

849
01:54:13,256 --> 01:54:15,129
All right, hold on.

850
01:54:32,650 --> 01:54:34,477
Kryptonite.

851
01:54:39,616 --> 01:54:41,573
You're asking yourself, "How?"

852
01:54:43,369 --> 01:54:48,327
Didn't your dad ever teach you
to look before you leap?

853
01:54:52,378 --> 01:54:55,333
Crystals. They're amazing, aren't they?

854
01:54:55,506 --> 01:54:58,757
They inherit the traits
of the minerals around them...

855
01:54:58,927 --> 01:55:03,719
...kind of like a son
inheriting the traits of his father!

856
01:55:06,517 --> 01:55:11,512
You took away five years of my life,
I'm just returning the favor!

857
01:55:15,027 --> 01:55:18,062
I'm still Superman!

858
01:55:26,704 --> 01:55:30,121
Get up! Come on!

859
01:57:02,175 --> 01:57:04,169
Now, fly.

860
01:58:05,282 --> 01:58:08,235
So long, Superman.

861
01:58:10,703 --> 01:58:13,788
<i>Your leadership can stir others...</i>

862
01:58:13,957 --> 01:58:16,115
<i>... to their own capacities
for moral betterment.</i>

863
01:58:16,293 --> 01:58:19,246
<i>The human heart is still subject
to monstrous deceits.</i>

864
01:58:22,883 --> 01:58:25,753
<i>Our destruction could have been avoided.
At this very moment...</i>

865
01:58:25,927 --> 01:58:27,551
<i>... I could embrace you in my arms.</i>

866
01:58:27,720 --> 01:58:30,128
<i>Your help would be called for endlessly.
Remember me.</i>

867
01:58:30,306 --> 01:58:33,640
<i>Even for those tasks which human beings
could solve themselves.</i>

868
01:58:44,071 --> 01:58:46,906
<i>Remember me, Kal-El.</i>

869
01:58:47,073 --> 01:58:48,983
<i>Remember me.</i>

870
01:58:57,876 --> 01:58:59,620
Superman's down there.

871
01:59:00,628 --> 01:59:03,001
- You sure?
- Yeah.

872
01:59:13,475 --> 01:59:16,096
- Richard!
- Yeah, I saw him. Strap in.

873
01:59:44,840 --> 01:59:46,631
Lois!

874
01:59:47,969 --> 01:59:49,760
Don't move.

875
02:00:35,850 --> 02:00:37,890
Come on, come on, come on.

876
02:00:41,647 --> 02:00:43,355
Richard!

877
02:00:43,524 --> 02:00:44,899
I'm trying! It's too choppy!

878
02:00:54,034 --> 02:00:55,613
Oh, my God.

879
02:02:43,311 --> 02:02:45,304
How did you find me?

880
02:02:50,819 --> 02:02:52,444
Thank you.

881
02:03:07,419 --> 02:03:09,328
What are you doing?

882
02:03:12,508 --> 02:03:13,753
I have to go back.

883
02:03:16,470 --> 02:03:18,213
You're hurt!

884
02:03:28,690 --> 02:03:30,351
Goodbye, Lois.

885
02:04:40,763 --> 02:04:43,088
<i>The technology on Krypton,
Superman 's home world...</i>

886
02:04:43,266 --> 02:04:45,591
<i>... was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.</i>

887
02:04:45,768 --> 02:04:47,144
<i>Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.</i>

888
02:04:47,311 --> 02:04:51,144
<i>Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...</i>

889
02:04:51,316 --> 02:04:53,273
<i>... would be indistinguishable from magic.</i>

890
02:04:53,443 --> 02:04:56,859
<i>But imagine: Cities, vehicles, weapons...</i>

891
02:04:57,030 --> 02:04:59,521
<i>... entire continents, all grown.</i>

892
02:04:59,700 --> 02:05:01,443
Lex?

893
02:05:03,286 --> 02:05:06,406
Are billions of people really going to die?

894
02:05:12,921 --> 02:05:14,629
Yes.

895
02:05:41,992 --> 02:05:43,321
Lex, what's happening?

896
02:05:49,291 --> 02:05:50,915
Go, go, go. Get to the helicopter.

897
02:05:53,796 --> 02:05:56,168
Go! Out, out! Now!

898
02:05:59,343 --> 02:06:02,510
No, no, no, take nothing!
Take nothing! Go, go!

899
02:06:04,431 --> 02:06:06,009
Got it.

900
02:06:50,144 --> 02:06:51,722
Here.

901
02:07:15,629 --> 02:07:17,586
- What did you do?
- I'm sorry!

902
02:07:17,756 --> 02:07:19,333
No!

903
02:07:38,902 --> 02:07:42,484
- What did you do?
- I'm sorry!

904
02:11:42,064 --> 02:11:43,558
Watch it.

905
02:11:44,941 --> 02:11:47,148
- Clear a path.
- Clear the way.

906
02:11:47,694 --> 02:11:49,319
- Move!
- Trauma One.

907
02:11:50,698 --> 02:11:53,023
- Where we going?
- Trauma One. Here it is.

908
02:11:58,872 --> 02:12:00,580
Watch it!

909
02:12:08,424 --> 02:12:09,799
Got him!

910
02:12:13,470 --> 02:12:14,846
Okay, I think I got it.

911
02:12:19,434 --> 02:12:22,270
Penetrating side wound
to right part of lower back.

912
02:12:23,606 --> 02:12:24,768
No hemorrhage.

913
02:12:29,445 --> 02:12:30,773
Shock at 200.

914
02:12:30,946 --> 02:12:32,773
Is that enough? He's not human.

915
02:12:32,948 --> 02:12:34,609
All right, charge to three, 360.

916
02:12:34,783 --> 02:12:36,362
Clear!

917
02:13:07,025 --> 02:13:08,305
It's kind of morbid, Perry.

918
02:13:09,152 --> 02:13:11,608
Always be prepared.

919
02:13:13,989 --> 02:13:15,698
How is she?

920
02:13:35,220 --> 02:13:38,220
Thank you. Thanks, baby.

921
02:13:41,017 --> 02:13:42,263
- Lois?
- Yeah.

922
02:13:44,438 --> 02:13:46,347
We can leave whenever you're ready.

923
02:13:46,523 --> 02:13:48,100
I mean...

924
02:13:49,692 --> 02:13:51,685
...you don't have to be here.

925
02:13:52,904 --> 02:13:54,731
Where else would I be?

926
02:13:54,906 --> 02:13:58,441
<i>Police have surrounded the area in order
to control thousands of visitors...</i>

927
02:13:58,618 --> 02:14:00,527
<i>... who have arrived
to show their support.</i>

928
02:14:00,704 --> 02:14:02,495
<i>Many are carrying signs and banners...</i>

929
02:14:02,664 --> 02:14:04,075
I could drive.

930
02:14:04,248 --> 02:14:06,704
<i>- No official announcements
over the past few hours...</i>

931
02:14:06,876 --> 02:14:09,450
<i>... but unconfirmed reports
from inside tell us...</i>

932
02:14:09,629 --> 02:14:11,421
<i>... the Man of Steel lies in a coma...</i>

933
02:14:11,590 --> 02:14:16,133
<i>... his condition unchanged
since he was admitted late yesterday.</i>

934
02:14:21,308 --> 02:14:24,558
<i>- Doctors have been vigilant in their...
- Foreign exchange markets...</i>

935
02:14:25,020 --> 02:14:28,057
- Where are you going?
- To the hospital.

936
02:14:28,231 --> 02:14:31,102
I'd be careful down there, guys.
It's a madhouse.

937
02:14:40,828 --> 02:14:43,947
- So much for parking.
- Do you think I can get in?

938
02:14:44,706 --> 02:14:47,577
You're Lois Lane. They'll let you in.

939
02:14:48,543 --> 02:14:51,379
I wanna go with Mommy.

940
02:15:12,568 --> 02:15:14,227
Taxi.

941
02:15:14,403 --> 02:15:15,862
I'll be right here.

942
02:15:23,161 --> 02:15:25,284
Watch your head, okay? Here we go.

943
02:15:57,363 --> 02:15:59,320
This way, Miss Lane.

944
02:16:21,513 --> 02:16:24,513
Mommy? Is he gonna get better?

945
02:16:26,559 --> 02:16:29,180
- I don't know.
- I want him to.

946
02:16:30,646 --> 02:16:32,853
I like him.

947
02:16:35,568 --> 02:16:37,228
Me too.

948
02:17:08,393 --> 02:17:11,180
I don't know if you can hear me.

949
02:17:13,816 --> 02:17:17,314
They say sometimes
that when people are...

950
02:17:20,322 --> 02:17:23,073
That sometimes they can hear you.

951
02:17:29,373 --> 02:17:31,615
I don't know if you can hear me.

952
02:17:40,592 --> 02:17:43,165
I wanted to tell you...

953
02:18:38,484 --> 02:18:40,393
Come on, honey.

954
02:19:24,113 --> 02:19:26,189
Step back, please!

955
02:19:43,383 --> 02:19:47,131
Lex, we only have six of those!

956
02:19:49,014 --> 02:19:50,294
Six?

957
02:19:54,102 --> 02:19:58,431
I would trade 300,000 coconuts...

958
02:19:58,606 --> 02:20:00,932
...and every ounce of your blood...

959
02:20:01,109 --> 02:20:05,736
...for a quart of gasoline!

960
02:20:06,490 --> 02:20:09,158
But what will we have to eat?

961
02:22:45,316 --> 02:22:47,356
You will be different.

962
02:22:51,030 --> 02:22:53,985
Sometimes, you will feel like an outcast.

963
02:22:55,159 --> 02:22:57,864
But you'll never be alone.

964
02:23:00,248 --> 02:23:02,918
You will make my strength your own.

965
02:23:05,878 --> 02:23:09,580
You will see my life through your eyes...

966
02:23:10,466 --> 02:23:15,841
...as your life will be seen through mine.

967
02:23:27,443 --> 02:23:31,487
The son becomes the father...

968
02:23:33,198 --> 02:23:37,944
